{
  "discussion": "Lewis argues that both of his convictions for gross sexual imposition were not supported by sufficient evidence. The court analyzed the sufficiency of the evidence by examining S.J.'s testimony regarding each of the alleged incidents. S.J. testified that Lewis would come over before her mother got home from work, sit on the bottom bunk of the bunkbed while she sat on his lap, and put one hand around her waist and the other hand down her pants, beneath her underwear, and rub her vaginal area. She also testified that this happened several times at her grandmother's house. Regarding the incident in the Ford Expedition, S.J. indicated that Lewis was driving Emily's vehicle and had her sit on his lap and let her help to steer the vehicle. While her hands were on the wheel, Lewis reached his hand down her pants and touched her vaginal area. S.J. stated that she asked him to stop and pulled his hand away, but he continued to touch her vaginal area until they arrived at his home. S.J. also testified that she was seven or eight around the time that her mom was dating Lewis and that she was twelve years old at the time of the trial. The court concluded that S.J.'s testimony provided some evidence that substantiates each of the essential elements of the offenses that were alleged to have occurred at the Tully Street house and in the Ford Expedition. The court also determined that the evidence presented at trial was sufficient to establish venue for the charge arising from the alleged incident in the Ford Expedition. The court further concluded that S.J.'s testimony provided some evidence from which a trier of fact could infer that the purpose of Lewis's alleged contact was sexual arousal or gratification. The court found that the evidence presented at trial was sufficient to support Lewis's convictions for gross sexual imposition. Lewis's second assignment of error is, therefore, overruled."
